WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.400 --> 00:00:04.050
ALAN PRICE: My
name is Alan Price,

00:00:04.050 --> 00:00:07.470
and I'm honored to serve as
director here at the John F.

00:00:07.470 --> 00:00:10.560
Kennedy Presidential
Library and Museum.

00:00:10.560 --> 00:00:12.680
Together with my colleague,
Steven Rothstein,

00:00:12.680 --> 00:00:15.870
who is director of the
Kennedy Library Foundation,

00:00:15.870 --> 00:00:18.120
and both of our
teams, we welcome you

00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:21.660
to the PEN/Hemingway
Award Ceremony.

00:00:21.660 --> 00:00:23.520
I would like to
acknowledge all those

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:25.950
who make this event
possible, including

00:00:25.950 --> 00:00:29.850
the many sponsors listed in your
program, whose representatives

00:00:29.850 --> 00:00:32.310
and leaders are
present with us today,

00:00:32.310 --> 00:00:37.140
and who also join in welcoming
all of you, both here

00:00:37.140 --> 00:00:40.800
and online, for today's
celebration of writers,

00:00:40.800 --> 00:00:45.720
writing, and the power
of a writer's voice.

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:48.990
PEN America and the
Hemingway Foundation partner

00:00:48.990 --> 00:00:51.060
with the Hemingway
Family Award to make

00:00:51.060 --> 00:00:53.958
this extraordinary
award possible.

00:00:53.958 --> 00:00:56.250
We are thrilled to have
members of the Hemingway family

00:00:56.250 --> 00:01:00.360
joining us, here in Boston
and watching online.

00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:03.270
Our greetings go out
over the livestream

00:01:03.270 --> 00:01:07.830
to Ernest Hemingway's son,
Patrick, and his wife, Carol,

00:01:07.830 --> 00:01:10.590
who are watching from
their home in Montana.

00:01:10.590 --> 00:01:12.420
Patrick and Carol
are the vanguard

00:01:12.420 --> 00:01:15.210
of support for the
PEN/Hemingway Award

00:01:15.210 --> 00:01:19.290
and for the Ernest Hemingway
Collection that resides here

00:01:19.290 --> 00:01:21.810
in the John F. Kennedy Library.

00:01:21.810 --> 00:01:24.510
We are honored to be
the world's largest

00:01:24.510 --> 00:01:27.840
repository for the
writer's personal papers,

00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:31.050
photographs, and mementos.

00:01:31.050 --> 00:01:33.630
Patrick's annual readings
from his father's works

00:01:33.630 --> 00:01:36.420
at the PEN/Hemingway
Ceremony had for decades

00:01:36.420 --> 00:01:39.960
been an important moment
for us here at the library.

00:01:39.960 --> 00:01:42.840
And now, stepping into his
uncle's role this year,

00:01:42.840 --> 00:01:46.480
is the writer's grandson,
Dr. Séan Hemingway.

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:48.930
He and his wife, Dr.
Colette Hemingway,

00:01:48.930 --> 00:01:52.920
co-chair the Hemingway
Council, which raises funds for

00:01:52.920 --> 00:01:55.350
and awareness of the collection.

00:01:55.350 --> 00:01:58.080
And we are delighted to welcome
Séan and Colette's daughter,

00:01:58.080 --> 00:02:02.460
Anouk Hemingway, the
writer's great granddaughter.

00:02:02.460 --> 00:02:06.540
One of the reasons I was
drawn to the Kennedy Library

00:02:06.540 --> 00:02:10.350
and excited by the opportunity
to lead this great institution

00:02:10.350 --> 00:02:13.380
is the fact that we
preserve and provide access

00:02:13.380 --> 00:02:16.650
to the Ernest
Hemingway Collection.

00:02:16.650 --> 00:02:20.100
With over 90% of his
manuscripts and papers

00:02:20.100 --> 00:02:24.150
and over 10,000
photographs and artifacts,

00:02:24.150 --> 00:02:28.740
we hold this jewel of a
collection in the public trust.

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:32.460
As Mrs. Jacqueline Kennedy
Onassis expressed it

00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:35.640
so well in a letter to
Mary Hemingway, quote,

00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:38.910
"I would be so proud
to have Jack's papers

00:02:38.910 --> 00:02:40.230
in Ernest Hemingway's library."

00:02:43.140 --> 00:02:46.170
Ernest Hemingway's writings
captured my attention

00:02:46.170 --> 00:02:50.710
and imagination and inspired me
throughout my formative years.

00:02:50.710 --> 00:02:52.500
I particularly
enjoyed those moments

00:02:52.500 --> 00:02:55.080
when I felt like I
was eavesdropping

00:02:55.080 --> 00:02:59.760
on dangerous situations and
important conversations.

00:02:59.760 --> 00:03:02.640
I encountered a romanticism
and heroism that

00:03:02.640 --> 00:03:04.980
ennobled me to dream bigger.

00:03:04.980 --> 00:03:09.810
There was tragedy that made me
a more compassionate person.

00:03:09.810 --> 00:03:13.350
President Kennedy admired
courage, particularly courage

00:03:13.350 --> 00:03:17.100
in the public sector, as
an all too rare virtue

00:03:17.100 --> 00:03:21.840
worthy of our study,
admiration, and recognition.

00:03:21.840 --> 00:03:25.320
How do we best develop
courage in people?

00:03:25.320 --> 00:03:28.460
Reading Ernest
Hemingway couldn't hurt.

00:03:28.460 --> 00:03:31.520
Ernest Hemingway contributed
greatly to my development

00:03:31.520 --> 00:03:33.230
as a human being.

00:03:33.230 --> 00:03:36.680
In keeping with the ideals
of the liberal arts,

00:03:36.680 --> 00:03:38.660
Hemingway harness
the power of language

00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:43.790
to develop in me the powers
of observation, appreciation,

00:03:43.790 --> 00:03:46.120
and healthy skepticism.

00:03:46.120 --> 00:03:51.460
This informal education on life
also carried a secret lesson--

00:03:51.460 --> 00:03:53.440
how to write.

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:56.830
Hemingway shaped my conscious
and intuitive appreciation

00:03:56.830 --> 00:04:00.460
of great writing and the
beauty of the English language

00:04:00.460 --> 00:04:05.180
that emerges when one strips
away ornamentation and allows

00:04:05.180 --> 00:04:09.980
the reader's imagination to
fill in the details of a story.

00:04:09.980 --> 00:04:12.380
Now that I am here at
the Kennedy Library

00:04:12.380 --> 00:04:14.270
and have the
occasional privilege

00:04:14.270 --> 00:04:18.230
of holding in my hands
some of his handwriting,

00:04:18.230 --> 00:04:21.800
and typing, and drafting,
and redrafting, and editing,

00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:25.730
and corresponding, and
cutting, and the craftsmanship

00:04:25.730 --> 00:04:30.680
and hard work that go into the
creation of a sentence that

00:04:30.680 --> 00:04:34.440
tries to say something
true, my life

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:37.110
has come full circle
to better understand

00:04:37.110 --> 00:04:42.470
my own life as a creation
of Hemingway's genius.

00:04:42.470 --> 00:04:45.050
I would like to now
share and contrast

00:04:45.050 --> 00:04:47.590
to fragments of writing.

00:04:47.590 --> 00:04:50.090
One comes from Ernest Hemingway.

00:04:50.090 --> 00:04:53.390
It is the first sentence
of a short story titled

00:04:53.390 --> 00:04:55.063
"The Capital of the World."

00:04:55.063 --> 00:04:55.730
You may know it.

00:04:59.040 --> 00:05:02.280
"Madrid is full of
boys named Paco,

00:05:02.280 --> 00:05:05.790
which is the diminutive
of the name Francisco,

00:05:05.790 --> 00:05:10.170
and there is a Madrid joke about
a father who came to Madrid

00:05:10.170 --> 00:05:14.220
and inserted an advertisement
in the personal columns of El

00:05:14.220 --> 00:05:19.920
Liberal which said, 'Paco,
meet me at Hotel Montana noon

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:25.200
Tuesday, all is forgiven, Papa,'
and how a squadron of Guardia

00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:29.670
Civil had to be called out
to disperse the 800 men who

00:05:29.670 --> 00:05:33.040
answered the advertisement."

00:05:33.040 --> 00:05:35.140
I do love that sentence.

00:05:35.140 --> 00:05:38.530
Within it is a whole
story, a whole world.

00:05:38.530 --> 00:05:41.770
It was published in 1936.

00:05:41.770 --> 00:05:45.220
I first read the
story in 1979, which

00:05:45.220 --> 00:05:47.710
happened to be the year that
this Kennedy Library was

00:05:47.710 --> 00:05:48.820
dedicated.

00:05:48.820 --> 00:05:51.160
And some of you, I
have reminded today,

00:05:51.160 --> 00:05:52.900
were here for that dedication.

00:05:52.900 --> 00:05:54.820
Welcome back.

00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:59.260
This past January, in an attempt
to create something positive

00:05:59.260 --> 00:06:01.960
during the time of a
government shutdown,

00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:04.750
I put pen to paper in
my own humble attempt

00:06:04.750 --> 00:06:06.610
to write a true sentence.

00:06:06.610 --> 00:06:10.070
The following sentence emerged.

00:06:10.070 --> 00:06:13.280
"Having planned and
attained the perfect weight

00:06:13.280 --> 00:06:15.890
at the anticipated
Saturday, Hector

00:06:15.890 --> 00:06:21.260
ate a carefully measured pound
of cheese smothered nachos

00:06:21.260 --> 00:06:24.920
and announced from his back
porch to family and neighbors

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:29.750
that his body was now
precisely 1% nacho

00:06:29.750 --> 00:06:34.070
before blowing out the candles
and making his only birthday

00:06:34.070 --> 00:06:36.020
wish that would
actually come true."

00:06:38.960 --> 00:06:41.810
As I sit here it,
our challenge now,

00:06:41.810 --> 00:06:45.740
faced by so many writers
who look to papa's writings

00:06:45.740 --> 00:06:50.660
like a beacon, is to do the work
necessary to prove ourselves

00:06:50.660 --> 00:06:55.250
more than lesser
copies of the original.

00:06:55.250 --> 00:06:59.240
And now it is my pleasure to
introduce Dr. Séan Hemingway.

00:06:59.240 --> 00:07:03.380
Dr. Hemingway is the John
A. and Carol O. Moran

00:07:03.380 --> 00:07:08.000
Curator in Charge of New York's
Metropolitan Museum of Art.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.700
He is a renowned
archaeologist with a specialty

00:07:10.700 --> 00:07:13.490
in Greek and Roman
bronzes and has

00:07:13.490 --> 00:07:16.760
excavated prehistoric,
classical, and Roman

00:07:16.760 --> 00:07:19.700
sites in Greece and Spain.

00:07:19.700 --> 00:07:22.850
He received his doctorate
from Bryn Mawr College,

00:07:22.850 --> 00:07:25.850
studied as a Fulbright
Scholar at the American School

00:07:25.850 --> 00:07:29.960
of Classical Studies in Athens,
and has been a visiting curator

00:07:29.960 --> 00:07:32.510
at the American Academy in Rome.

00:07:32.510 --> 00:07:35.450
He is the author of numerous
scholarly publications,

00:07:35.450 --> 00:07:39.170
including The Horse and
Jockey from Artemision--

00:07:39.170 --> 00:07:43.100
A Bronze Equestrian Monument
of the Hellenistic Period

00:07:43.100 --> 00:07:46.760
and of the novel The
Tomb of Alexander.

00:07:46.760 --> 00:07:49.730
He is also editor of the
Hemingway Library Editions

00:07:49.730 --> 00:07:51.770
of Ernest Hemingway's works.

00:07:51.770 --> 00:07:55.880
Please join me in welcoming to
our stage Dr. Séan Hemingway.

00:07:55.880 --> 00:07:59.317
[APPLAUSE]

00:08:06.200 --> 00:08:07.720
SEAN HEMINGWAY: Thank you, Alan.

00:08:07.720 --> 00:08:10.030
Good afternoon,
ladies and gentlemen.

00:08:10.030 --> 00:08:13.210
It is a privilege for me to be
here with you this afternoon

00:08:13.210 --> 00:08:16.120
and represent the
Hemingway family.

00:08:16.120 --> 00:08:18.880
For many years, as Alan
said, my uncle Patrick,

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:22.000
Ernest Hemingway's second
son, would read something

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.120
from his father's
work at this event,

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:27.850
and I would like to
continue that tradition.

00:08:27.850 --> 00:08:32.440
Patrick and Carol Hemingway
are watching the livestream

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:35.549
of this today in
their home in Montana,

00:08:35.549 --> 00:08:37.150
and so I send them
warm greetings

00:08:37.150 --> 00:08:38.950
and a big thank you
for all that they

00:08:38.950 --> 00:08:43.712
have done to support great
literature and the Hemingway

00:08:43.712 --> 00:08:45.670
Collection here at the
John F. Kennedy Library.

00:08:50.130 --> 00:08:53.260
The passage I'm going to read
to you as an unpublished account

00:08:53.260 --> 00:08:56.680
of the Spanish Civil War from
my grandfather's paper here

00:08:56.680 --> 00:08:58.980
at the Kennedy.

00:08:58.980 --> 00:09:03.060
It was written by Ernest
Hemingway in the summer of 1936

00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:05.500
and will be included in the
forthcoming Hemingway Library

00:09:05.500 --> 00:09:08.830
Edition of his novel For
Whom the Bell Tolls, which

00:09:08.830 --> 00:09:10.330
will be published in July.

00:09:14.260 --> 00:09:16.980
Here it is.

00:09:16.980 --> 00:09:20.910
"During the last 15 months,
I saw murder done in Spain

00:09:20.910 --> 00:09:23.710
by the fascist invaders.

00:09:23.710 --> 00:09:26.290
Murder is different from war.

00:09:26.290 --> 00:09:28.870
Men can hate war and
be opposed to it,

00:09:28.870 --> 00:09:31.240
yet become accustomed
to it as a way of life

00:09:31.240 --> 00:09:34.970
when it is fought to defend
your country against an invader

00:09:34.970 --> 00:09:39.220
and for your right to live
and work as a free man.

00:09:39.220 --> 00:09:42.850
In such a case no
man who is a man

00:09:42.850 --> 00:09:46.360
gives any importance to his life
because so much more important

00:09:46.360 --> 00:09:48.830
things are at stake.

00:09:48.830 --> 00:09:52.880
A man observing this same
war and writing of it

00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:55.010
cares nothing for
his life either

00:09:55.010 --> 00:09:58.470
if he believes in the
necessity of what he is doing.

00:09:58.470 --> 00:10:02.330
He cares only to
write the truth.

00:10:02.330 --> 00:10:05.780
So when the German Messerschmitt
plane dives on your car

00:10:05.780 --> 00:10:09.080
with all four machine
guns chattering,

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:13.180
you swerve to the side of the
road and jump out of the car.

00:10:13.180 --> 00:10:17.650
You lie flat under a tree if
there is a tree, or in a ditch

00:10:17.650 --> 00:10:19.360
if there's a ditch.

00:10:19.360 --> 00:10:22.970
Or sometimes you lie
in the open field.

00:10:22.970 --> 00:10:26.260
And when the plane comes
back to try to kill you again

00:10:26.260 --> 00:10:29.600
and as bullets throw dust
spouts over your back,

00:10:29.600 --> 00:10:33.980
you lie with your mouth dry,
but you laugh at the plane

00:10:33.980 --> 00:10:36.660
because you're alive.

00:10:36.660 --> 00:10:38.640
You have no hatred.

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:40.170
It is war.

00:10:40.170 --> 00:10:42.330
He thinks your
car is a staff car

00:10:42.330 --> 00:10:44.670
and he has a right to kill you.

00:10:44.670 --> 00:10:47.790
He does not kill
you, so you laugh.

00:10:47.790 --> 00:10:52.850
The Messerschmitt is too fast
for good ground strafing.

00:10:52.850 --> 00:10:54.650
When he pulls up
from the dive, he

00:10:54.650 --> 00:10:57.050
drops some little bombs
like hand grenades

00:10:57.050 --> 00:11:00.200
tied in bunches out of a chute.

00:11:00.200 --> 00:11:02.330
They make a big
flash and a roar,

00:11:02.330 --> 00:11:04.005
and there is a
roll of gray smoke.

00:11:06.670 --> 00:11:08.650
You're still alive,
and the Messerschmitt

00:11:08.650 --> 00:11:12.760
is gone, his motor in a whine
like a circular saw hitting

00:11:12.760 --> 00:11:15.380
a log in a lumber mill.

00:11:15.380 --> 00:11:19.340
You try to spit because you know
from experiment that you cannot

00:11:19.340 --> 00:11:22.760
spit if you are really scared.

00:11:22.760 --> 00:11:26.780
You find your mouth is too dry
to spit, and you laugh again,

00:11:26.780 --> 00:11:29.250
and that is all.

00:11:29.250 --> 00:11:31.110
There is no bitterness
when the fascists

00:11:31.110 --> 00:11:34.560
try to kill you because
they have a right to, even

00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:36.590
by mistake.

00:11:36.590 --> 00:11:40.700
But you have anger and hatred
when you see them do murder,

00:11:40.700 --> 00:11:44.438
and you see them do
it almost every day."

00:11:44.438 --> 00:11:46.422
Thank you.

00:11:46.422 --> 00:11:49.894
[APPLAUSE]

00:11:57.840 --> 00:12:00.720
