wanted to be a writer.

00:56:39.240 --> 00:56:41.640
Told my college
freshman roommate,

00:56:41.640 --> 00:56:43.530
I'm going to be a writer.

00:56:43.530 --> 00:56:45.330
And thinking of
Hemingway, I told him,

00:56:45.330 --> 00:56:49.650
I'm going to publish my
first novel when I'm 25.

00:56:49.650 --> 00:56:52.560
Got to 25, be another
19 years before I

00:56:52.560 --> 00:56:57.900
published my first novel, so
clearly I am no Hemingway.

00:56:57.900 --> 00:57:00.390
What I am is a refugee.

00:57:00.390 --> 00:57:01.950
And it may seem a
little odd for me

00:57:01.950 --> 00:57:03.450
to say that in
the present tense,

00:57:03.450 --> 00:57:05.790
because if you look at
me, it's clearly the case

00:57:05.790 --> 00:57:09.630
that I made the transition
from refugee to bourgeoisie

00:57:09.630 --> 00:57:10.410
a long time ago.

00:57:10.410 --> 00:57:13.763
[LAUGHTER]

00:57:15.200 --> 00:57:18.380
From camps to clubs.

00:57:18.380 --> 00:57:21.900
Very exclusive clubs, such as
the JFK Presidential Library.

00:57:21.900 --> 00:57:24.150
Such an honor to be here.

00:57:24.150 --> 00:57:27.140
And when I realized this event
would be hosted at the JFK

00:57:27.140 --> 00:57:29.840
Presidential Library, I
remembered that I had actually

00:57:29.840 --> 00:57:33.980
quoted John F. Kennedy earlier
this semester in my class

00:57:33.980 --> 00:57:36.590
on the American War in Vietnam,
so on the airplane flight

00:57:36.590 --> 00:57:41.120
over, I looked up my PowerPoint
slide to that quotation.

00:57:41.120 --> 00:57:44.600
John F. Kennedy was a
senator at the time in 1957,

00:57:44.600 --> 00:57:46.980
and of course, Indochina,
as it was called--

00:57:46.980 --> 00:57:48.800
Laos, Cambodia, and Vietnam--

00:57:48.800 --> 00:57:51.920
were on the American radar.

00:57:51.920 --> 00:57:54.920
And speaking of Indochina,
John F. Kennedy said,

00:57:54.920 --> 00:57:59.760
"This is our offspring."

00:57:59.760 --> 00:58:03.750
So as one of JFK's offspring,
I would like to say, dad,

00:58:03.750 --> 00:58:04.320
I'm home.

00:58:04.320 --> 00:58:07.792
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:11.205 --> 00:58:12.830
Coming to United
States was not exactly

00:58:12.830 --> 00:58:14.000
like coming home for me.

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:15.470
I was a refugee, as I mentioned.

00:58:15.470 --> 00:58:18.680
I was born in 1971, came
here in 1975 at four

00:58:18.680 --> 00:58:23.508
years of age along with 130,000
other Vietnamese refugees.

00:58:23.508 --> 00:58:25.550
And we ended up in one of
four refugee camps that

00:58:25.550 --> 00:58:28.070
were set up to take care of us.

00:58:28.070 --> 00:58:30.472
Ours was Fort Indiantown
Gap in Pennsylvania.

00:58:30.472 --> 00:58:32.180
And in order to leave
one of these camps,

00:58:32.180 --> 00:58:35.990
a refugee had to have
a sponsor to guarantee

00:58:35.990 --> 00:58:39.110
that they wouldn't be a
drain on the American state.

00:58:39.110 --> 00:58:41.480
The problem for
my family of four

00:58:41.480 --> 00:58:44.990
was that there was not a sponsor
who would take all four of us.

00:58:44.990 --> 00:58:46.790
So one sponsor took my parents.

00:58:46.790 --> 00:58:48.680
One sponsor took my
10-year-old brother.

00:58:48.680 --> 00:58:51.170
One sponsor took
four-year-old me.

00:58:51.170 --> 00:58:53.840
And that's where
my memories began,

00:58:53.840 --> 00:58:58.070
being taken away from my
parents howling and screaming.

00:58:58.070 --> 00:59:00.362
And I'm a father now of a
five and a half year-old son,

00:59:00.362 --> 00:59:02.487
and when he turned four,
it was the occasion for me

00:59:02.487 --> 00:59:04.040
to look back on
this time in my life

00:59:04.040 --> 00:59:07.730
that I had tried to suppress,
it had been so painful.

00:59:07.730 --> 00:59:09.770
And I realized that I
had not forgotten it,

00:59:09.770 --> 00:59:11.810
that it had been
an invisible brand

00:59:11.810 --> 00:59:15.050
stamped between my shoulder
blades for decades.

00:59:15.050 --> 00:59:18.493
But also as an
adult, as a parent,

00:59:18.493 --> 00:59:19.910
I could look at
my parents and see

00:59:19.910 --> 00:59:22.940
what they must have felt
having their sons taken away

00:59:22.940 --> 00:59:23.800
from them.

00:59:23.800 --> 00:59:26.480
And we were taken away from
them for a good reason, which

00:59:26.480 --> 00:59:30.480
was to help my parents find the
time to get back on their feet.

00:59:30.480 --> 00:59:33.000
That's not the case in
terms of what's happening

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:34.530
at our southern border.

00:59:34.530 --> 00:59:37.440
When I think about what happened
to myself and my brother,

00:59:37.440 --> 00:59:39.540
I empathize deeply
with what's happening

00:59:39.540 --> 00:59:42.210
with families that are having
their children separated

00:59:42.210 --> 00:59:42.720
from them.

00:59:42.720 --> 00:59:46.020
I know that it is wrong
and it is inhumane

00:59:46.020 --> 00:59:47.790
what we are doing at
our southern border

00:59:47.790 --> 00:59:49.588
with the families
that are coming here.

00:59:49.588 --> 00:59:53.046
[APPLAUSE]

00:59:58.442 --> 01:00:00.400
Those families, the
parents and their children,

01:00:00.400 --> 01:00:03.940
will be scarred for life if my
experience is any indication.

01:00:03.940 --> 01:00:05.410
And I was comparatively lucky.

01:00:05.410 --> 01:00:07.660
I was only taken away from
my family for three months.

01:00:07.660 --> 01:00:09.880
My brother, who is
seven years older,

01:00:09.880 --> 01:00:13.160
didn't come home for two years.

01:00:13.160 --> 01:00:16.930
And that's why he
likes to say to me,

01:00:16.930 --> 01:00:18.370
mom and dad love you more.

01:00:18.370 --> 01:00:21.830
[LAUGHTER]

01:00:21.830 --> 01:00:23.145
Don't feel too bad for him.

01:00:23.145 --> 01:00:25.520
Seven years after coming to
this country with no English,

01:00:25.520 --> 01:00:27.428
he went to Harvard.

01:00:27.428 --> 01:00:28.970
And then, just to
rub it in because I

01:00:28.970 --> 01:00:31.190
went to my last
choice college, he

01:00:31.190 --> 01:00:33.290
went to Stanford
Medical School, which

01:00:33.290 --> 01:00:35.510
is what you're supposed
to do when you're Asian.

01:00:35.510 --> 01:00:38.835
[LAUGHTER]

01:00:40.740 --> 01:00:44.460
So clearly being a
refugee is not all bad,

01:00:44.460 --> 01:00:46.260
and that was the
case for me as well.

01:00:46.260 --> 01:00:47.885
I did get some good
things out of being

01:00:47.885 --> 01:00:51.682
a refugee, such as the
requisite emotional damage

01:00:51.682 --> 01:00:52.890
necessary to become a writer.

01:00:52.890 --> 01:00:56.790
[LAUGHTER]

01:00:56.790 --> 01:00:59.700
And as a father, I've done my
best to pass on that legacy

01:00:59.700 --> 01:01:00.270
to my son.

01:01:00.270 --> 01:01:03.285
[LAUGHTER]

01:01:03.285 --> 01:01:04.660
Five and a half
years old, like I

01:01:04.660 --> 01:01:07.550
said, like most five and a
half year-olds, he loves LEGOs.

01:01:07.550 --> 01:01:09.310
Always asking for LEGOs.

01:01:09.310 --> 01:01:12.040
And if you're a parent, you
know you cannot always say yes

01:01:12.040 --> 01:01:13.600
to what your children want.

01:01:13.600 --> 01:01:16.970
So sometimes I have to say,
no, you cannot get these LEGOs.

01:01:16.970 --> 01:01:19.300
And I ask him, you
know why you're not

01:01:19.300 --> 01:01:21.130
going to get these LEGOs?

01:01:21.130 --> 01:01:22.830
And he thinks about
it for a while,

01:01:22.830 --> 01:01:24.755
and he says, because
you're a refugee.

01:01:24.755 --> 01:01:28.044
[LAUGHTER]

01:01:31.537 --> 01:01:32.680
I say, that's right.

01:01:32.680 --> 01:01:34.030
[LAUGHTER]

01:01:34.030 --> 01:01:36.850
I want him to remember that
both of his parents are refugees

01:01:36.850 --> 01:01:39.310
and that all four of his
grandparents are refugees.

01:01:39.310 --> 01:01:42.850
And it seems crucial to
remind a young boy of this

01:01:42.850 --> 01:01:45.010
at this time in
our history, when

01:01:45.010 --> 01:01:48.160
we were undergoing the worst
refugee crisis in world history

01:01:48.160 --> 01:01:49.830
since World War II.

01:01:49.830 --> 01:01:52.510
The United Nations says
approximately 68 million people

01:01:52.510 --> 01:01:55.120
are displaced, 22 million
of whom are officially

01:01:55.120 --> 01:01:57.250
classified as refugees.

01:01:57.250 --> 01:01:59.110
And I am certain that
many of the people who

01:01:59.110 --> 01:02:00.700
are coming to our
southern border

01:02:00.700 --> 01:02:04.270
are refugees, whether the United
Nations calls them that or not,

01:02:04.270 --> 01:02:06.715
whether we call
them that or not.

01:02:06.715 --> 01:02:08.590
Of course, the President
of the United States

01:02:08.590 --> 01:02:11.160
calls these refugees animals.

01:02:11.160 --> 01:02:15.370
And as a refugee, I object
to this characterization.

01:02:15.370 --> 01:02:17.680
And I object because I
myself have experienced

01:02:17.680 --> 01:02:20.770
some of the sting
of dehumanization,

01:02:20.770 --> 01:02:23.660
beginning with when my
family moved from Harrisburg,

01:02:23.660 --> 01:02:26.230
Pennsylvania to San
Jose, California in 1978,

01:02:26.230 --> 01:02:29.170
and my parents opened perhaps
the second Vietnamese grocery

01:02:29.170 --> 01:02:30.850
store in San Jose,
which is what you're

01:02:30.850 --> 01:02:33.573
supposed to do when you're
a refugee or an immigrant

01:02:33.573 --> 01:02:34.240
to this country.

01:02:34.240 --> 01:02:36.432
You're supposed to pursue
the American dream.

01:02:36.432 --> 01:02:38.890
So it was kind of a shock when
I walk down the street, when

01:02:38.890 --> 01:02:40.630
I was around 10 or
11 years old, and saw

01:02:40.630 --> 01:02:44.800
a sign in another window that
said, another American driven

01:02:44.800 --> 01:02:48.570
out of business
by the Vietnamese.

01:02:48.570 --> 01:02:51.680
And I thought, does
this person know

01:02:51.680 --> 01:02:56.820
that my parents work 12
to 14 hour days every day

01:02:56.820 --> 01:02:58.620
in this shop?

01:02:58.620 --> 01:03:01.890
Does this person know
that my parents were shot

01:03:01.890 --> 01:03:05.010
in the store on Christmas Eve?

01:03:05.010 --> 01:03:10.780
Does this person know anything
about who my parents are

01:03:10.780 --> 01:03:14.900
and what they've had to go
through to get to this country

01:03:14.900 --> 01:03:17.200
and to open this door?

01:03:17.200 --> 01:03:19.510
And of course, that
person did not know that,

01:03:19.510 --> 01:03:22.090
did not care to know
anything about my parents,

01:03:22.090 --> 01:03:25.890
saw them as less than human.

01:03:25.890 --> 01:03:31.370
The saddest thing about this was
that I internalized that sign.

01:03:31.370 --> 01:03:34.850
I remember going to high school,
to the most elite high school

01:03:34.850 --> 01:03:37.670
in San Jose, California, a
primarily white high school,

01:03:37.670 --> 01:03:40.287
but there were a handful of
us who were of Asian descent.

01:03:40.287 --> 01:03:41.870
And we knew we were
different, we just

01:03:41.870 --> 01:03:44.017
had a hard time
putting into words.

01:03:44.017 --> 01:03:45.600
So every day at
lunch, we would gather

01:03:45.600 --> 01:03:48.750
in a corner of the campus,
and we would call ourselves

01:03:48.750 --> 01:03:50.140
the Asian Invasion.

01:03:50.140 --> 01:03:53.336
[LAUGHTER]

01:03:54.483 --> 01:03:56.900
Funny thing is, I went back
to my campus a couple of years

01:03:56.900 --> 01:03:59.480
ago to give a speech, and
we really have taken over.

01:03:59.480 --> 01:04:02.952
[LAUGHTER]

01:04:03.950 --> 01:04:06.920
Where do we get this idea
of the Asian invasion from?

01:04:06.920 --> 01:04:10.400
At least partly from movies,
from American popular culture

01:04:10.400 --> 01:04:11.390
that we had absorbed.

01:04:11.390 --> 01:04:13.310
For me, it was all of
the American movies

01:04:13.310 --> 01:04:14.810
about the Vietnam
War that Hollywood

01:04:14.810 --> 01:04:16.880
was putting forth in
the '70s and the '80s,

01:04:16.880 --> 01:04:19.940
but very particularly
Apocalypse Now.

01:04:19.940 --> 01:04:22.880
I remember watching that when
I was 10 or 11 years old, much

01:04:22.880 --> 01:04:26.030
too young of an age,
way too precocious.

01:04:26.030 --> 01:04:28.655
And I was someone who
loved American war movies.

01:04:28.655 --> 01:04:31.407
I identified with American
soldiers, John Wayne and so on.

01:04:31.407 --> 01:04:32.990
And so when I was
watching this movie,

01:04:32.990 --> 01:04:35.030
I was identifying
with American soldiers

01:04:35.030 --> 01:04:38.630
up until the point they
killed Vietnamese civilians.

01:04:38.630 --> 01:04:41.180
And then I was split in two.

01:04:41.180 --> 01:04:43.610
Was I the American
doing the killing,

01:04:43.610 --> 01:04:46.310
or was I the Vietnamese
being killed?

01:04:46.310 --> 01:04:50.270
Well, that experience convinced
me of the power of stories.

01:04:50.270 --> 01:04:52.700
I was already in love with
stories as a young refugee

01:04:52.700 --> 01:04:55.580
because I found so much comfort
and solace from the refugee

01:04:55.580 --> 01:04:57.230
life in stories.

01:04:57.230 --> 01:05:01.250
But watching Apocalypse Now and
movies like it also crushed me

01:05:01.250 --> 01:05:03.080
and convinced me of
the power of stories

01:05:03.080 --> 01:05:06.080
to destroy us as
well as save us.

01:05:06.080 --> 01:05:07.940
And I think that was
the moment that I

01:05:07.940 --> 01:05:12.290
began hoping to be a
writer because I thought,

01:05:12.290 --> 01:05:16.070
one day, one day I will
take revenge on Hollywood.

01:05:16.070 --> 01:05:17.730
[LAUGHTER]

01:05:17.730 --> 01:05:21.740
Which is exactly what
happened in The Sympathizer.

01:05:21.740 --> 01:05:24.710
But I was yearning
for representation,

01:05:24.710 --> 01:05:26.820
although that was not the
word I would have used.

01:05:26.820 --> 01:05:28.487
And I think I shared
something in common

01:05:28.487 --> 01:05:30.200
with so many of us
who have suffered

01:05:30.200 --> 01:05:33.800
from a lack of representation,
from misrepresentation,

01:05:33.800 --> 01:05:35.960
from under representation.

01:05:35.960 --> 01:05:40.940
We know that not having enough
representation is dangerous.

01:05:40.940 --> 01:05:44.600
Not having enough representation
can actually destroy lives.

01:05:44.600 --> 01:05:50.030
Not having enough representation
can psychically destroy lives.

01:05:50.030 --> 01:05:52.730
So there's a great urgency
to the task of representation

01:05:52.730 --> 01:05:56.030
that so many of us as writers
and storytellers and artists

01:05:56.030 --> 01:05:56.710
feel.

01:05:56.710 --> 01:05:58.820
And so it's difficult
for me to say

01:05:58.820 --> 01:06:01.820
that as much as
representations matter,

01:06:01.820 --> 01:06:05.450
as much as we need more stories
and voices and representatives,

01:06:05.450 --> 01:06:09.532
perhaps it's
actually not enough.

01:06:09.532 --> 01:06:11.990
I'll give you the example of
the publishing industry, which

01:06:11.990 --> 01:06:13.670
seems very relevant today.

01:06:13.670 --> 01:06:17.900
The publishing
industry is 87% white.

01:06:17.900 --> 01:06:22.220
And in 1955, James Baldwin, in
his book Notes of a Native Son,

01:06:22.220 --> 01:06:26.780
could write, "The world
is white no longer,

01:06:26.780 --> 01:06:30.000
and it will never
be white again."

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:34.260
But a publishing industry
that lionizes James Baldwin

01:06:34.260 --> 01:06:39.490
and yet is still 87% white,
is still quite white.

01:06:39.490 --> 01:06:43.080
So we have a lot of work
to do, because insomuch

01:06:43.080 --> 01:06:45.510
as we have representation and
representatives in figures

01:06:45.510 --> 01:06:48.030
like James Baldwin, and Toni
Morrison, and Ta-Nehisi Coates,

01:06:48.030 --> 01:06:50.830
and so on and so forth,
so many great writers,

01:06:50.830 --> 01:06:53.160
there is still nevertheless
the persistence

01:06:53.160 --> 01:06:57.300
of racial and economic
inequality in our civilization.

01:06:57.300 --> 01:07:01.110
And for me, what that
means is not simply

01:07:01.110 --> 01:07:04.740
that there's inequality but
that there is the persistence

01:07:04.740 --> 01:07:07.290
of colonization.

01:07:07.290 --> 01:07:11.370
Now, some of you in the room
are thinking, what colonization?

01:07:11.370 --> 01:07:14.220
Well, the United
States is an example

01:07:14.220 --> 01:07:16.117
of successful colonization.

01:07:16.117 --> 01:07:17.700
Usually when we think
of colonization,

01:07:17.700 --> 01:07:20.490
we think of France in
Indochina, for example,

01:07:20.490 --> 01:07:23.220
which colonized Indochina
for 80 or so years

01:07:23.220 --> 01:07:27.090
and then was defeated
and kicked out.

01:07:27.090 --> 01:07:29.400
Successful
colonization, however,

01:07:29.400 --> 01:07:34.050
is successful at renaming
itself so that it is not

01:07:34.050 --> 01:07:36.420
called colonization.

01:07:36.420 --> 01:07:39.030
In the United States,
successful colonization

01:07:39.030 --> 01:07:42.560
is called the American dream.

01:07:42.560 --> 01:07:45.440
Successful colonization is
never called colonization

01:07:45.440 --> 01:07:48.290
for the same reason that
successful treason is never

01:07:48.290 --> 01:07:50.240
called treason,
for the same reason

01:07:50.240 --> 01:07:53.937
that successful war crimes
are never called war crimes.

01:07:53.937 --> 01:07:56.270
If we look back upon our
history at the founding moments

01:07:56.270 --> 01:07:59.030
of our country, which is
what Tommy Orange's novel,

01:07:59.030 --> 01:08:01.640
There There, does in
its first 20 pages.

01:08:01.640 --> 01:08:03.440
And if you read the
first 20 pages--

01:08:03.440 --> 01:08:04.857
and this my
interpretation, Tommy.

01:08:04.857 --> 01:08:05.990
You may disagree with me.

01:08:05.990 --> 01:08:06.530
I'm used to that.

01:08:06.530 --> 01:08:07.760
I'm a professor and a scholar.

01:08:07.760 --> 01:08:09.177
Writers are always
saying, I don't

01:08:09.177 --> 01:08:10.710
know what you're talking about.

01:08:10.710 --> 01:08:13.190
But when I read the first
20 pages of Tommy Orange's

01:08:13.190 --> 01:08:15.220
There There, I
can't help but think

01:08:15.220 --> 01:08:18.859
that would be very hard to deny
that this country was built

01:08:18.859 --> 01:08:22.729
on the foundation of genocide,
and not just genocide,

01:08:22.729 --> 01:08:29.750
but slavery, occupation,
war, and racism as well.

01:08:29.750 --> 01:08:33.560
The United States is a
successful colonizing country,

01:08:33.560 --> 01:08:36.950
and if we need further evidence
of that it is that whenever

01:08:36.950 --> 01:08:39.920
the United States has had
the choice between choosing

01:08:39.920 --> 01:08:42.890
the sides of the colonized
or the colonizer,

01:08:42.890 --> 01:08:46.250
it has almost always chosen the
side of the colonizer, which

01:08:46.250 --> 01:08:50.620
is what happened in the
1940s and 1950s in Indochina.

01:08:50.620 --> 01:08:52.700
The United States had
the opportunity to side

01:08:52.700 --> 01:08:54.830
with Vietnam, Laos, or Cambodia.

01:08:54.830 --> 01:08:57.620
Instead, it chose
willingly to take over

01:08:57.620 --> 01:08:59.990
the war from the French.

01:08:59.990 --> 01:09:03.870
Now I said this in my
novel, The Sympathizer,

01:09:03.870 --> 01:09:05.729
and something
interesting happened

01:09:05.729 --> 01:09:07.100
after that novel came out.

01:09:07.100 --> 01:09:09.100
In the first major
review of the novel,

01:09:09.100 --> 01:09:11.430
in the second or third
line, the reviewer said,

01:09:11.430 --> 01:09:15.750
"Viet is the voice
for the voiceless."

01:09:15.750 --> 01:09:18.330
And I was like, no, have
you ever actually met

01:09:18.330 --> 01:09:21.109
any Vietnamese people?

01:09:21.109 --> 01:09:24.990
We're really, really loud.

01:09:24.990 --> 01:09:28.920
The problem is not that
we don't have voices.

01:09:28.920 --> 01:09:32.540
The problem is that
we're not heard.

01:09:32.540 --> 01:09:35.120
Now this phrase, the
voice for the voiceless,

01:09:35.120 --> 01:09:36.680
I'm sure you've heard it before.

01:09:36.680 --> 01:09:38.930
Maybe you've used it yourself.

01:09:38.930 --> 01:09:40.880
It's a dangerous
sentiment, even though it

01:09:40.880 --> 01:09:43.399
sounds like a compliment.

01:09:43.399 --> 01:09:46.069
And the reason why it's
a dangerous sentiment,

01:09:46.069 --> 01:09:48.950
because what it implies is
that people would much rather

01:09:48.950 --> 01:09:56.270
hear one voice, rather than
a chorus, or a cacophony,

01:09:56.270 --> 01:09:58.080
or a community.

01:09:58.080 --> 01:10:01.860
The desire to hear the
voice for the voiceless

01:10:01.860 --> 01:10:05.730
is itself a symptom
of colonization.

01:10:05.730 --> 01:10:09.090
If we would rather hear
a voice of the voiceless

01:10:09.090 --> 01:10:12.960
than abolish the conditions
of voicelessness, then

01:10:12.960 --> 01:10:16.510
we've resigned ourselves
to, or agree with,

01:10:16.510 --> 01:10:19.400
colonization's persistence.

01:10:19.400 --> 01:10:21.390
So representation matters.

01:10:21.390 --> 01:10:24.840
We need writers,
but it's not enough.

01:10:24.840 --> 01:10:28.712
What we need is decolonization.

01:10:28.712 --> 01:10:29.295
Colonization--

01:10:29.295 --> 01:10:31.140
[APPLAUSE]

01:10:31.140 --> 01:10:32.100
Thank you.

01:10:34.977 --> 01:10:35.810
I must be in Boston.

01:10:35.810 --> 01:10:39.310
[LAUGHTER]

01:10:40.310 --> 01:10:44.450
Colonization has resulted in
a massive transfer of wealth

01:10:44.450 --> 01:10:48.020
to the colonized and
their descendants.

01:10:48.020 --> 01:10:51.150
So what would we need to do?

01:10:51.150 --> 01:10:54.990
Greater taxation,
redistribution,

01:10:54.990 --> 01:10:58.920
universal health care,
child care, education,

01:10:58.920 --> 01:11:03.870
abolishing the prison-industrial
complex, demilitarization,

01:11:03.870 --> 01:11:08.540
reparations, and
yes, representation.

01:11:08.540 --> 01:11:10.890
So on this list, you can
clearly see that representation

01:11:10.890 --> 01:11:13.530
is the easiest
task, which is why

01:11:13.530 --> 01:11:15.990
we tend to focus
on it, especially

01:11:15.990 --> 01:11:18.270
in the world of literature.

01:11:18.270 --> 01:11:21.570
Now, novels themselves
cannot decolonize.

01:11:21.570 --> 01:11:24.600
But novels can
depict colonization,

01:11:24.600 --> 01:11:29.070
can depict the processes and
the dreams of decolonization.

01:11:29.070 --> 01:11:30.810
I can think of
many books that do.

01:11:30.810 --> 01:11:32.820
I'll give you a few
here to show you

01:11:32.820 --> 01:11:36.670
that it's not actually
impossible to have

01:11:36.670 --> 01:11:38.620
a literature of decolonization.

01:11:38.620 --> 01:11:41.890
Books that I have found striking
in recent years have included--

01:11:41.890 --> 01:11:45.790
Han Kang's Human Acts, which
is about the Korean military

01:11:45.790 --> 01:11:48.970
dictatorship's suppression
of a democratic uprising

01:11:48.970 --> 01:11:53.298
in Guangzhou in 1980 in Korea;
António Lobo Antunes' The Land

01:11:53.298 --> 01:11:55.840
at the End of the World, which
was a touchstone for me when I

01:11:55.840 --> 01:11:58.750
was writing The Sympathizer,
which is about the Portuguese

01:11:58.750 --> 01:12:02.110
Colonial War in Angola from
the perspective of a reluctant

01:12:02.110 --> 01:12:05.840
soldier; Laila Lalami's
The Moor's Account,

01:12:05.840 --> 01:12:08.470
which is the account of
the first black slave taken

01:12:08.470 --> 01:12:12.070
by Spanish conquistadors to
the Americas; and, of course,

01:12:12.070 --> 01:12:15.550
Tommy Orange's
There There as well.

01:12:15.550 --> 01:12:17.230
The problem that in
the United States

01:12:17.230 --> 01:12:20.410
our dominant literature, in
contemporary American fiction

01:12:20.410 --> 01:12:24.010
at the very least,
tends to be apolitical.

01:12:24.010 --> 01:12:26.500
Decolonization is
beyond the horizon

01:12:26.500 --> 01:12:30.100
of most of our contemporary
American writers.

01:12:30.100 --> 01:12:33.290
That doesn't mean it should
be beyond our imagination.

01:12:33.290 --> 01:12:35.200
Now, even for those of
us who are committed

01:12:35.200 --> 01:12:37.570
to decolonization, who
imagine ourselves working

01:12:37.570 --> 01:12:39.340
not just in the
solitude of our rooms

01:12:39.340 --> 01:12:41.980
but in the solidarity of
social and political movements

01:12:41.980 --> 01:12:46.480
that transform the landscape,
those of us who are doing

01:12:46.480 --> 01:12:49.210
this work or imagine
ourselves doing this work

01:12:49.210 --> 01:12:53.260
should not call ourselves
the voices for the voiceless.

01:12:53.260 --> 01:12:57.100
We should imagine ourselves
as one voice among many,

01:12:57.100 --> 01:12:59.290
among the many social and
political movements that

01:12:59.290 --> 01:13:04.960
are committed to abolishing
the conditions of voicelessness

01:13:04.960 --> 01:13:09.750
that make it so easy to
privilege us as writers.

01:13:09.750 --> 01:13:15.230
So looking back to my teenage
self, proto-Asian Invasion,

01:13:15.230 --> 01:13:20.360
I realize now that I was living
in conditions of voicelessness.

01:13:20.360 --> 01:13:23.420
I was living in conditions
of narrative scarcity.

01:13:23.420 --> 01:13:26.330
And what that means is that when
you live in narrative scarcity,

01:13:26.330 --> 01:13:29.150
almost none of the
stories are about you.

01:13:29.150 --> 01:13:31.100
So any story that
comes out about you

01:13:31.100 --> 01:13:32.550
takes on tremendous weight.

01:13:32.550 --> 01:13:34.940
It's an unfair burden
of representation

01:13:34.940 --> 01:13:38.432
put on these few voices or
these few representatives.

01:13:38.432 --> 01:13:39.890
So when Crazy Rich
Asians came out,

01:13:39.890 --> 01:13:41.890
all the Asians freaked
out, like, oh my god!

01:13:41.890 --> 01:13:43.077
There's a movie about us!

01:13:43.077 --> 01:13:44.660
Too bad it's a bad
movie, but it's OK.

01:13:44.660 --> 01:13:47.859
[LAUGHTER]

01:13:48.542 --> 01:13:49.250
I'm just kidding.

01:13:49.250 --> 01:13:51.780
I actually haven't
seen Crazy Rich Asians.

01:13:51.780 --> 01:13:53.377
I'm a bad Asian.

01:13:53.377 --> 01:13:54.710
I did listen to the book though.

01:13:57.360 --> 01:13:59.790
The opposite of
narrative scarcity

01:13:59.790 --> 01:14:01.320
is narrative plenitude.

01:14:01.320 --> 01:14:04.560
That's when almost all of
the stories are about you.

01:14:04.560 --> 01:14:06.990
That's how you know
you have privilege,

01:14:06.990 --> 01:14:10.890
when you can take it for granted
that almost all of the stories

01:14:10.890 --> 01:14:12.030
are about you.

01:14:12.030 --> 01:14:14.310
Abolishing the conditions
of voicelessness

01:14:14.310 --> 01:14:15.900
is about achieving
narrative plenitude

01:14:15.900 --> 01:14:20.010
for everyone in our society,
not just for the majority

01:14:20.010 --> 01:14:22.920
or the wealthy or
the privileged.

01:14:22.920 --> 01:14:25.380
So looking back on my
teenage self, the self

01:14:25.380 --> 01:14:30.070
so desperately in need of
more voices, more stories,

01:14:30.070 --> 01:14:34.370
it's clear that one of the
causes for that condition

01:14:34.370 --> 01:14:39.590
was structural racism,
structural inequality.

01:14:39.590 --> 01:14:43.500
But there was one
other major factor.

01:14:43.500 --> 01:14:47.300
I'm going to leave you with
that as a parting public service

01:14:47.300 --> 01:14:51.860
announcement, one last
factor for why there

01:14:51.860 --> 01:14:55.130
are so few stories by Vietnamese
and Asian-Americans out there.

01:14:55.130 --> 01:14:57.730
Do you know what it is?

01:14:57.730 --> 01:14:59.310
Asian parents.

01:14:59.310 --> 01:15:01.450
[LAUGHTER]

01:15:01.450 --> 01:15:02.215
Asian parents.

01:15:05.200 --> 01:15:08.440
Asian parents out
there, or you who

01:15:08.440 --> 01:15:12.800
will one day be Asian parents
or parents of Asian children,

01:15:12.800 --> 01:15:15.470
do not crush the
hopes and dreams

01:15:15.470 --> 01:15:18.380
of your artistic children.

01:15:18.380 --> 01:15:23.300
Nourish them, nurture
them, help them grow,

01:15:23.300 --> 01:15:26.850
until one day they
too can become

01:15:26.850 --> 01:15:30.660
writers writing scathing
autobiographies featuring you.

01:15:30.660 --> 01:15:34.060
[LAUGHTER]

01:15:34.060 --> 01:15:34.850
Boston, thank you.

01:15:34.850 --> 01:15:35.600
You've been great.

01:15:35.600 --> 01:15:38.842
[APPLAUSE]

01:16:09.830 --> 01:16:11.710
ALAN PRICE: In a
moment, I hope you

01:16:11.710 --> 01:16:14.210
will be able to join us in
the pavilion, where we'll

01:16:14.210 --> 01:16:16.220
be able to shake hands,
greet each other,

01:16:16.220 --> 01:16:18.980
and celebrate these
marvelous writers.

01:16:18.980 --> 01:16:21.260
Again, as we exit,
I would ask you

01:16:21.260 --> 01:16:23.510
to join me for one
more round of applause

01:16:23.510 --> 01:16:25.925
for all you have done
to enrich the world.

01:16:25.925 --> 01:16:29.390
[APPLAUSE]

01:16:31.370 --> 01:16:33.230
Thank you for being
with us this afternoon.

01:16:33.230 --> 01:16:36.580
[APPLAUSE]

